# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1875-new-york-mutuals-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-new-york-mutuals-season] The New York Mutuals baseball team finished second in the National Association in 1874.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1875 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their fourth consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 71–8 to win the pennant by 15 games.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 62 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 54 wins.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Deacon White (.367), second baseman Ross Barnes (.364), and first baseman Cal McVey (.355) finished 1–2–3 in the league's batting race.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] McVey paced the circuit with 87 runs batted in, and outfielder Jim O'Rourke had the most home runs, with 6.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Boston offense scored more runs than any other team in the NA.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] According to the FiveThirtyEight ELO rating system, they are the greatest team of all time.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] This was the last season of the Association, which dissolved at the end of the year.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings club would join the new National League in 1876.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **Brooklyn Atlantics** played in 1875 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished eleventh in the league with a record of 2–42.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The league folded at the conclusion of the season, and the Atlantics did not join the National League which succeeded it in 1876.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] In their second season in the National Association, the **1875 Hartford Dark Blues** finished in third place.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] They were managed by starting third baseman Bob "Death to Flying Things" Ferguson.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] The Dark Blues, with future Hall of Famer Candy Cummings, had the best pitching staff in baseball.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] Cummings won 35 games, and the 19-year-old Tommy Bond finished second in league ERA at 1.56.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] Following the season, they were one of the NA teams chosen to join the new National League.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-keokuk-westerns-season] The **Keokuk Westerns** played their first and only season of professional baseball in 1875 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-keokuk-westerns-season] They finished thirteenth in the league with a record of 1–12.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-new-york-mutuals-season] The New York Mutuals baseball team finished sixth in the National Association in 1875.
[src:1875-new-york-mutuals-season/1875-new-york-mutuals-season] The league folded after this season and the Mutuals joined the new National League in 1876.
